result.execSummary:
Christopher J. Goyer was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Christopher J. Goyer was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Case called at 2:42pm [mo]
Defendant Christopher J. Goyer in court, in custody.   ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.

Defendant admits service of the Warrant Criminal Complaint and Warrant; the Defendant waives the reading of the documents
Right to Counsel given; Mr. Goyer indicates that he does not wish to have counsel.
The Court finds the waiver of right to counsel has been made freely, voluntarily and intelligently. 
The Court finds that Mr. Goyer is competent to represent himself.

Mr. Goyer indicates that he wishes to waive his right to an extradiction hearing. 
Upon direction of the Court, Mr. Goyer reads and signs appropriate waiver documents. 
ADA Beck presents the documents to the Court.
The Court finds that Mr. Goyer has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his right to an Extradiction Hearing in Wisconsin.
The Court grants the Illinois State authorities approval to come to Wisconsin to retrieve Mr. Goyer. 
recess: 2:50pm
